<div class="gem-c-govspeak govuk-govspeak direction-ltr">
      <div class="govspeak">
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>

<p>The feature shared by all of the schools who had increased their English Baccalaureate (EBacc) entry rates was that they had introduced some form of ‘compulsion’ to students studying EBacc subjects at key stage 4 (KS4).</p>

<h3 id="ebacc-option-pathways">EBacc option pathways</h3>

<p>They were doing this in one of 3 ways:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
<a href="#making-ebacc-subjects-compulsory-for-all">making the study of EBacc subjects compulsory for all</a> (except the very lowest ability pupils)</li>
  <li><a href="#routing-pupils-into-an-ebacc-pathway">routing certain students into an EBacc pathway at key stage 4</a></li>
  <li>
<a href="#offering-free-options">allowing free choice of options</a> but strongly encouraging EBacc subject take up</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="delivery-strategies">Delivery strategies</h3>

<p>This shift to compelling more students into what was seen as a more academically rigorous set of options was being balanced with ways to increase pupil engagement, enthusiasm and achievement. Strategies for this comprised:</p>

<ul>
  <li>addressing modern foreign languages (MFL)</li>
  <li>making MFL relevant and engaging</li>
  <li>raising the quality of provision</li>
  <li>liaising with feeder schools</li>
  <li>supporting pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds</li>
  <li>supporting pupils with lower ability levels</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="strategic-changes">Strategic changes</h3>

<p>To successfully implement this approach schools were making strategic changes to underpin this cultural shift. This involved:</p>

<ul>
  <li>having high aspirations</li>
  <li>getting parents on board</li>
  <li>securing staffing</li>
  <li>ensuring progression routes</li>
  <li>reflecting and developing</li>
</ul>

<p>Case studies of how these approaches looked in the schools interviewed are included.</p>

<h2 id="setting-up-ebacc-pathways">Setting up EBacc pathways</h2>

<p>Schools had implemented one of three different pathways to studying EBacc subjects which had led to their increased entry levels. They had weighed up the pro’s and con’s of each approach and selected the one that best fit their school, values and ethos.</p>

<p>The pathways were:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="#making-ebacc-subjects-compulsory-for-all">making EBacc subjects compulsory</a></li>
  <li><a href="#routing-pupils-into-an-ebacc-pathway">routing pupils into an EBacc pathways</a></li>
  <li><a href="#offering-free-options">offering ‘free options’</a></li>
</ul>

<p>Considerations for any of these approaches include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>how to deal with subject dropping</li>
  <li>ensuring a broad and balanced curriculum offer</li>
  <li>time allocation</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="making-ebacc-subjects-compulsory-for-all">Making EBacc subjects compulsory for all</h3>

<p>This approach generally involves having all of the EBacc subjects as compulsory ‘options’ to study at KS4.</p>

<p>Therefore all students study English, mathematics and science (choosing combined or individual sciences), select a modern foreign language, a humanities subject and then have between 1 and 4 additional choices.</p>

<p>Schools have other compulsory subjects including RE, PE and PHSE to fit into timetabling.</p>

<p>In a few cases students can pick more than one of the EBacc options, so for example study both geography and history, or choose to study more than one MFL.</p>

<h4 id="sandy-upper-school-example">Sandy Upper School example</h4>

<div class="call-to-action">
<p>School background:</p>

<ul>
  <li>foundation school in the East of England who were rated as inadequate by Ofsted in 2011 but improved to good by 2017</li>
  <li>increased EBacc entry rates from 9.1% in 2011 to 79.1% in 2017</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>Their options booklet states: “Students joining Sandy Upper School in year 9 follow a broad and balanced curriculum having already made their option choices before the start of the year.</p>

<p>The vast majority of students follow a core curriculum of English Language, English Literature, Mathematics, Science, Humanities and a Modern Foreign Language. This group of subjects forms the English Baccalaureate.”</p>

<h3 id="routing-pupils-into-an-ebacc-pathway">Routing pupils into an EBacc pathway</h3>

<p>In this approach instead of having EBacc subjects compulsory for all students, there was a pathway of set options that includes all of the EBacc subjects (as set out above) and certain students are encouraged to follow this at KS4. Often it is pupils with the lowest ability levels in English and mathematics (and who are therefore deemed to require more input on these, or to follow a less rigorously academic pathway) who get to select a different ‘route’ or set of options (where for example they choose a MFL or a humanities subject, or have completely free choice over their non-compulsory options).</p>

<p>The decision of which pathway which students follow is agreed between teaching staff, heads of department, parents and the child. Often this was informed by KS2 assessment data and progress in KS3.</p>

<h4 id="leretraite-roman-catholic-girls-school-example">LeRetraite Roman Catholic Girls School example</h4>

<div class="call-to-action">
<p>School background:</p>

<ul>
  <li>34.7% of pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds</li>
  <li>increased EBacc entry rates from 11.6% in 2011 to 66.9% in 2016</li>
  <li>progress 8 score of 0.67</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>The school has set up 4 ‘routes’ of options, 2 of which include the study of all EBacc subjects (the variation being on whether students study combined or triple science). This means that their options blocks are:</p>

<p>The Core Curriculum (a group of subjects that all students must study):</p>

<ul>
  <li>English</li>
  <li>English literature</li>
  <li>mathematics</li>
  <li>science (double science)</li>
  <li>physical education (non examination)</li>
  <li>religious studies</li>
</ul>

<p>The Option Choices (from which they select 3):</p>

<ul>
  <li>one subject from:
    <ul>
      <li>French</li>
      <li>Spanish</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>one subject from:
    <ul>
      <li>history</li>
      <li>geography</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>one subject from:
    <ul>
      <li>art, craft and design (Art)</li>
      <li>art and design (textiles)</li>
      <li>art and design (3D design)</li>
      <li>business and economics (economics)</li>
      <li>computer science</li>
      <li>drama</li>
      <li>French</li>
      <li>geography</li>
      <li>history</li>
      <li>music</li>
      <li>Spanish</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 id="offering-free-options">Offering free options</h3>

<p>In schools without a specific EBacc route students are given greater opportunity to select EBacc subjects by having these appear more frequently in more option blocks.</p>

<p>This type of approach is supported by clear information on what the school believes are the benefits of studying the EBacc subjects and considerations for pupils making their KS4 options. Advice is often for pupils to choose these subjects, in order to show their ability to future employers or universities.</p>

<h4 id="darrick-wood-school-example">Darrick Wood School example</h4>

<div class="call-to-action">
<p>School background:</p>

<ul>
  <li>academy in Outer London with 258 pupils in KS4</li>
  <li>increased EBacc entry rates from 18% in 2011 to 86.8% in 2017</li>
  <li>rated outstanding</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>All students select one subject from each of the 4 option blocks. This results in all students studying a MFL, but also by having humanities subjects in multiple blocks students are helped to select one, or both of them too.</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Block A</th>
      <th>Block B</th>
      <th>Block C</th>
      <th>Block D</th>
      <th> </th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
